<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-03-25T10:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-03-25T10:00:00-05:00" n="621" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d621">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">811.20 Defense(M)Peru/64: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to the Ambassador in Peru</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Norweb</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-03-25T11:00:00-04:00">March 25,
                                    1942—11 a.m.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>259. Your 284 of March 21. Rubber Reserve informs us that price offered
                            by Rubber Reserve Company for Peruvian rubber is exactly same as price
                            being paid Brazil for same grade. Point can be quickly cleared up when
                            Dasso is here.</p>
                        <p>Any question of establishing tire factory in Peru is probably out of
                            question as far as this country is concerned.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Welles</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>